en: The Life and Exploits of the Ingenious Gentleman Don Quixote de la Mancha
J. and R. Tonson & R. Dodsley
RETRATO DE CERVANTES DE SAAVEDRA POR EL MISMO.
f.p. 1 or The Life of Cervantes

Cervantes' portrait as a writer (holding a quill, at his library...) and as a soldier (helmet and sword on the wall).In the background, Don Quixote and Sancho Panza represented in an ambiguous way. Are they real? (in a window) or fictitious? (in a painting).Large size figure.Drawing and engraving are excellent.This portrait will be copied time and time again.
1 - William Kent's signature appears as "G. Kent".2 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
1.1 DQ at his library reading chivalric novels

Don Quixote, dressed as a 18th century English gentleman, reads peacefully while he observes his family arms (over the fireplace); these, far from looking like "tomadas de orín y llenas de moho, luengos siglos había, que estaban puestas y olvidadas en un rincón" (1:1), appear new and neat.Drawing and engraving are excellent (don Quixote's figure, furniture, books, arms...); not so the room, too small, cold and without details.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote arrives at the inn and encounters two ladies
2.2. DQ arrives at inn (castle)2.3. DQ received by ”ladies”

Don Quixote mounted on Rocinante (the innkeeper holds its reins) arrives at the inn.Two "ladies" ("mujeres del partido") try to run away afraid of him, but he calms them down (their faces do not represent fear).In the background, a swineherd blowing a horn; don Quixote confuses him with a dwarf welcoming the knight.The setting has nothing to do with real "manchegan" architecture.Drawing and engraving are excellent.

1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.2 - This plate (nº 3) has no signatures; neither by the painter nor by the engraver.3 - The original composition has been attributed to John Vanderbank, but the engraver, William Hogarth, made several changes in it (I179-183).
Don Quixote knighted by the innkeeper
3.4 DQ knighted at inn by innkeeper

In the center of the composition, don Quixote kneels before the innkeeper (holding a book and a sword).In the background, doña Molinera with don Quixote's spurs and doña Tolosa with his sword.In the foreground, a candle, held by a boy, creates interesting light and shadow effects (see innkeeper, don Quixote's armour...).Large size figures.Excellent drawing and engraving.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.2 - The figure of the innkeeper has been attributed to William Hogarth.
Scrutiny of don Quixote's library and housekeeper's fears

From the whole episode, Oldfield and Vanderbank have chosen a scene where the comical situation is not caused by don Quixote's madness, but by the ignorance and superstition of the housekeeper.In the center of the composition, the housekeeper, who "tornó luego con una escudilla de agua bendita, y un hisopo, y dijo: Tome vuestra Merced, Señor Licenciado, rocíe este aposento, no esté aquí algún encantador de los muchos que tienen estos libros, y nos encanten" (6:1); the priest, the niece and the barber listen to her.Monumental and solemn figures.The figure of the niece is worth noting.Drawing and engraving are excellent.Theatrical composition (curtains).
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote asks Sancho Panza to be his squire
7.4 Sancho Panza agrees to be his squire

Oldfield prefers scenes with dialogues or speeches where all the attention is in gestures, looks and faces.See, for instance, don Quixote's hands while he promises Sancho the government of an island, or Sancho's face while he listens to don Quixote attentively.Bucolic setting.Drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Sancho asks don Quixote for the island he was promised to govern
10.1 SP asks DQ for his insula

After having defeated the Basque (fallen in the background with three Basque ladies), don Quixote is asked by Sancho for the government of his island; the knight tells Sancho that he must wait (see don Quixote's hand).Don Quixote and Sancho's figures are well-detailed drawn and engraved; their gestures and faces are very remarkable.

1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.2 - In 1738, previous to this illustration, there was a tailpiece with don Quixote fighting with the Basque, but in 1742 this tailpiece has not been included.

In "Sobre las Estampas desta Historia" (I, i-viii), John Oldfield defends the selection of episodes with dialogues and speeches.In the center, don Quixote talks to several shepherds about the Golden Age; the shepherds listen to him captively and attentively.One shepherd (left foreground) is especially remarkable; his figure is classical.In contrast to this shepherd, Sancho does not listen to don Quixote and his only worry is eating; he looks like a gluttonous child (this figure is very different to those in other illustrations).Drawing and engraving are masterly.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Grisóstomo's burial and Marcela's appearance and speech
14.1 Episode of Grisóstomo and Marcela, continuation14.3 Marcela’s appearance and speech14.4 Burial of Grisóstomo

During Grisóstomo's burial (center of the composition), Marcela appears on a crag; Ambrosio, Grisóstomo's friend, accuses her of causing his death.One diagonal (narration) joins these three main characters: from Marcela, through Ambrosio's face and arm, to Grisóstomo.This diagonal keeps in balanced with two verticals (a gravedigger on the left and don Quixote on the right).The scene is observed by Sancho Panza and several shepherds.Illustration of great emotiveness and beauty; Grisóstomo's figure, as a classical young man, is very remarkable.Marcela appears as an idealized shepherdess.Drawing and engraving are masterly.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.2 - Notice that the original page reference (110) has been erased and re-engraved (65).
The innkeeper´s wife, her daughter and Maritornes take care of don Quixote
16.1 DQ and SP arrival at second inn

Accurate composition to Cervantes' text. "En esta maldita cama se acostó Don Quixote, y luego la ventera, y su hija le emplastaron de arriba a abajo, alumbrándoles Maritornes" (16:1).Innkeeper's wife and his daughter's figures are idealized, in contrast with Maritornes' caricature image.Sancho complains about his own pain too.Well-detailed drawing and engraving, with good light and shadow effects (produced by Maritornes' candle).
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote's night adventure with Maritornes

This episode was first represented by Savery (Dordrecht: Savery, 1675), but in a very different way.Savery was interested in the humorous fight between Sancho, Maritornes and the muleteer.Now, Olfield and Vanderbank have chosen a funny moment not because of the action, but of the dialogue.Don Quixote speaks to Maritornes as if she was a maiden and she flees away from him.On the left, the muleteer.In this illustration, the representation of Maritornes is quite different from that in the previous plate.Engraving and drawing are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.

From the whole episode, a comical/kind scene has been chosen to show the mutual care relation between don Quixote and Sancho.Don Quixote, after having fought with a flock of sheep, has been stoned by the shepherds; Sancho counts how many teeth remain in his mouth.Neither the previous fight nor the next scene (don Quixote and Sancho vomiting), both scenes of crude humour, were selected.In the background, the shepherds bringing the flock together.Drawing and engraving show Vanderbank's and Van der Gucht's marked and personal styles.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Sancho Panza ties Rocinante's hind legs

During the night (badly represented), the sound of fulling mills frightens Sancho; the squire decides to tie Rocinante's hind legs to prevent don Quixote from leaving him alone.From the whole adventure, a comical/ingenious situation was been chosen, not the next crude one (Sancho's mishap).Drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Sancho Panza contemplates the barber basin (Mambrino's helmet)
21.3 Adventure of the helmet of Mambrino

In the foreground, Sancho contemplates the "conquered" Mambrino's helmet, a barber basin, and exclaims "Por Dios, que la bacía es buena, y que vale un real de á ocho como un maravedí" (21:2), while don Quixote asks him to hand the basin to him.In the background, the defeated barber running away.Well-detailed drawing and engraving for Don Quixote and Sancho's figures.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote asks the galley slaves about their crimes

Good example of the kind of scenes chosen by Oldfield and Vanderbank to be represented.Previously (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657 and Amberes: Verdussen, 1672 - 1673), don Quixote had been represented fighting with the soldiers and stoned by the galley slaves; now, none of these scenes interest them.Don Quixote appears talking to the galley slaves (dialogue).Idealized image of the slaves, as "good savages".Excellent drawing and engraving (see gestures and hands: don Quixote, Sancho and slave on the left); the musculature of the slaves must be noted.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.

From the whole episode, instead of don Quixote and Cardenio's fight, their previous conversation has been selected; Sancho observes them.Cardenio represented as a "good savage".Large size figures, well drawn and engraved.Notice gestures (Cardenio and don Quixote's hands).
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote's love penance in Sierra Morena
25.4 SP’s embassy to Dulcinea;25.5 DQ performs mad acts

In Sierra Morena, don Quixote begins to do his love penance (some somersaults) before Sancho leaves for El Toboso to take don Quixote's letter for Dulcinea.In the foreground, don Quixote's arms and barber basin (Mambrino's helmet).Don Quixote's depiction is impossible.Sancho's drawing is not too much good.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Dorotea is discovered by the priest, barber and Cardenio
28.1 Priest, barber and Cardenio encounter Dorotea

Dorotea, washing her feet in a stream, is discovered by the priest, the barber and Cardenio.This scene will be habitual in future editions.Dorotea could never be confused with a man (as it is said in Cervantes' text); she has been represented in woman clothes and showing her bosom.Bucolic setting; well-detailed nature.Drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.2 - The original vol. and p. reference has been erased and re-engraved; notice the erased "I".

Princess Micomicona (Dorotea) knelt down before don Quixote but he tries to prevent her from doing it (see the gesture of his hand).Sancho Panza explains to don Quixote who Micomicona is; the barber, disguised with a beard, appears as her squire.In the background, Cardenio and the priest (they should appear hidden).Plate of great quality; masterly drawing and engraving (see Micomicona's face, don Quixote's hand...).
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
34.1 Reading of El curioso impertinente continues

A scene of great drama.This edition inaugurates the interest in the interpolated novels.Camila pretends to stab herself (it should be in the left shoulder) and Lotario and Leonela try to stop her; Anselmo, her husband, is hidden behind a tapestry (he should remain behind the tapestry during the whole scene).Theatrical and dramatic scene; well-resolved movement and commotion.Well-detailed and rich setting; drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.

Vandervank has chosen as main character of this scene something almost anecdotal; next to don Quixote, who is attacking the wineskins, appears Dorotea, turning her head to avoid seeing don Quixote; "que vió quan corta y sutilmente estaba vestido, no quiso entrar á ver la batalla de su ayudador" (35:1).Dorotea´s figure (designed with an spiral movement) is excellently-drawn and engraved.In the background, Sancho, the innkeeper (both gesticulating), the priest and Cardenio.Drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Dorotea knelt down before don Fernando
36.2 Resolution of love affairs of Cardenio and Luscinda, Dorotea and Don Fernando

Vanderbank emphasizes with his composition the four main characters:Dorotea knelt down before don Fernando, who let Luscinda go with Cardenio.The narration is developed through gestures and looks.In the background, the priest, the barber and Sancho.Foreground figures are excellently-drawn and engraved.Drawing and engraving are masterly.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Zoraida discovered by his father with the captive

Zoraida, surprised with the captive by her father (Agi Morato), pretends to faint.Zoraida and captive's group is of great beauty.Drawing and engraving are masterly.Not too much accurate setting; clothes and architectures do not look like Moorish; they are some kind of orientalist evocation.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote hung by his hand at the inn
43.2 Maritornes and innkeeper’s daughter hang DQ from window by a hand

Don Quixote, hung by his own hand tied to a window of the inn, remains standing on Rocinante while the innkeeper's daughter and Maritornes observe him from the inn courtyard.Not accurate representation; both girls should appear looking through the window.Drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote's speech about the barber basin (Mambrino's helmet) and the packsaddle
44.3 Beginning of the dispute about the packsaddle

This episode was first represented by Savery (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657), but he selected the fight; Oldfield and Vanderbank have chosen a speech.Don Quixote, holding the barber basin, tries to convince the barber (#2) of the real nature of the basin (Mambrino's helmet).Don Fernando, the priest, the barber (Maese Pedro) and Sancho Panza observe them.Next to Sancho, the packsaddle that he disputed with the barber (#2).The scene is comical because of the dialogue, not because of the action.Drawing and engraving are masterly.

1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.2 - "Esta escena, tan plácida y sosegada, es nada menos que la tremenda disputa sobre si la bacía era o no era el yelmo de Mambrino. Es imposible, sobre todo, prever que esa tranquila y mesurada conversación va a terminar en la descomunal sarracina que a Don Quijote le hizo recordar el campo de Agramante.Estosgentlemenquijotescos [...] discuten con toda flema, con breves frases, casi sin gestos; lo cual no excluye una verdadera pasión, pero concentrada y oculta, capaz de dar (como va a ocurrir aquí, en el Quijote), una vez agotados todos los razonamientos, en incalculable estallido" (Givanel 124-126).
Don Quixote arrested by the Holy Brotherhood

Simple and theatrical composition (all characters in the foreground as if they were on a stage).While don Quixote speaks, one of the officers of justice reads don Quixote's description to arrest him.It has not been chosen the later fight.Between them, the judge (Juan Pérez de Viedma) and the priest; on the left, the barber (#2?).Drawing and engraving are excellent; masterly large size figures.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote encounters some penitents with a sculpture of the Virgin Mary

From the whole episode, it has been chosen a non violent scene.Don Quixote orders the penitents to release the lady (a sculpture of the Virgin Mary) that they have taken prisoner.Sancho tries to stop him.The group of the penitents with the sculpture has a strong, expressive and plastic character, but it is not accurate to Spanish processions.Drawing and engraving are highly-remarkable.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Cervantes receives his arms to fight Chivalric Books

Allegorical frontispiece.Cervantes, as HerculesMusagetes(followed by the nine Muses), receives from a satyr the arms (Comedy mask) to fight the monsters (Chivalric books) that have invaded Mount Parnassus.Monumental figures of great and classical beauty.Excellent drawing and engraving (Muses' faces, tunics, Hercules' musculature...).
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.2 - According to its original page and volume reference, it should be placed in vol. I, as in 1738.
Cervantes receives his arms for fight chivalric books

Allegorical frontispiece.Cervantes, as Hercules Musagetes (followed by the nine Muses), receives from a satyr the arms (Comedy mask) to fight the monsters (Chivalric books) that have invaded Mount Parnassus.Monumental figures of great and classical beauty.Excellent drawing and engraving (Muses' faces, tunics, Hercule's musculature...)

1 - "No habiendo hallado (por más solicitud que se haya puesto) Retrato alguno de Miguel de Cervantes Saavedra; ha parecido conveniente poner en el frontispicio de su Historia de Don Quijote de la Mancha (principal obra suya, y la que hace, su memoria más durable) una Representación que figure, el gran designio que tuvo tan ingenioso Autor.Propuso éste como blanco de su pluma, derribar de la común estimación de los Españoles todas aquellas máquinas fantásticas de Libros de Caballerías, cuyos Héroes, concebidos en unas imaginaciones fecundas sí, pero delirantes, llegaron a ser la idea del valor, y trato civil; y quiso reestablecer al mismo tiempo la antigua, natural, y propia manera de tratar los asuntos proporcionados a una decorosa ficción.Para poder representar todo esto por medio del Diseño; el Monte Parnaso, asiento de las Musas, el cual se ve en la Estampa enseñoreado de Monstruos, y Quimeras de Libros de Caballerías, servirá para dar una bastante idea del desordenado, y extravagante Estado del orbe Literario en aquellos tiempos, y de la Reforma, de que tenía necesidad.Uno, y otro ejecutó nuestro Autor con feliz acierto, pues venció, desbarató, y acabó, toda la caterva de Caballeros Andantes, y de sus Encantadores, procurando vencerlos con sus propias fuerzas, quiero decir, figurando un héroe igualmente fantástico, pero de invención tan decorosa, que desbaratados, y deshechos ellos quedase como perpetuo triunfo, erigido en memoria de tan gloriosa hazaña.La principal Figura de la Representación Alegórica, es el Hércules llamado Musagetes, a quien atribuyó la Mitología la guía de las Musas, y por eso vemos en diferentes monumentos (a que ha perdonado la injuria de los tiempos,) que las va acompañando con una Lira en la mano, símbolo del conocimiento de las artes a que presiden ellas. Este Hércules pues con propiedad representa a nuestro Autor, aficionado a las Musas tan decorosamente, que poniendo en práctica lo más primoroso de las Artes, nos dejó en todas sus Obras, y especialmente en ésta una natural, y perfectísima idea de escribir entretenida, y gustosamente, así las cosas serias, como las burlescas; y procuró infundirnos cierta delicadeza de gusto, que si llega a percibirse, causa gran hastío de cuales quiera otros absurdos; y singular desprecio de los que neciamente los apadrinan.La ocupación de Hércules (según lo pide su carácter, y la alusión a nuestro Autor) es echar del Parnaso todos aquellos Monstruos, que habían ocupado el asiento de las Musas; y también restituirlas en su antigua posesión. Y en esta coyuntura se deja ver propiamente, no sólo como patrón de las Musas, y Destruidor de Monstruos en cualquiera parte, sino señaladamente en España, donde erigió las famosas Columnas trofeos de sus victorias, atendiendo a que ella fue el Teatro de sus más gloriosas acciones. En ella mató a Gerión, Rey del mismo País, de quien se cuenta que tenía triplicado cuerpo. En ella mató al Perro de dos cabezas, de ella echó también cierta raza muy extraña de ferocísimos Toros: bien que alguna que parece había quedado de aquella casta, hizo grandes estragos, hasta que nuestro Caballero Andante desarraigó en gran parte el antiguo abuso de pelear con tales animales: bien que es preciso confesar, que hasta el día de hoy no está su raza totalmente extinguida; puesto que todavía la gente del País, si alguna vez se pone a combatir con tan furiosos animales, suele llevar la pena de su temerario atrevimiento.El Sátiro, que en muchos antiguos monumentos se ve en la misma compañía, y en la misma postura, y acción, que las que aquí se representan, sirve en este lugar para manifestar el Genio placentero de Miguel de Cervantes; y aludiendo a esto, presenta a Hércules (símbolo de nuestro Autor) los instrumentos a propósito para lograr su fin; que fue ciertamente una Graciosidad satírica, simbolizada aquí por la Máscara, que es el don que se le ofrece" (Oldfield. "Sobre las Estampas desta Historia". I:i-ii) [Updated orthography].
Don Quixote talking to the priest and the barber
1.1 Priest and barber visit DQ to check if he is cured of his madness

In the foreground, as an intimist scene, don Quixote, sat on his bed, talks to the priest and the barber.Don Quixote and priest's gestures are highly-remarkable and theatrical.In the background, the housekeeper and the niece.Interest in dialogues.Drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
3.1 Sansón Carrasco visits DQ to tell him about the publication of his story, DQ Part I

Accurate to Cervantes' text: Sansón Carrasco "viendo á Don Quixote, poniéndose de rodillas, y diciéndole: Deme vuestra grandeza las manos, Señor Don Quixote de la Mancha; que por el hábito de San Pedro que visto, aunque no tengo otras órdenes que las cuatro primeras, que es vuestra merced uno de los más famosos Caballeros andantes" (3:2).Don Quixote's figure with dignity, but comical too.Sansón Carrasco's face shows his own personality.Sancho observes them amused.Drawing, shading and engraving are masterly.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Sancho talking with his wife, Teresa Panza, about his second sally
5.1 SP speaks with his wife Teresa

Interest in intimist and familiar scenes with dialogues.Teresa Panza answers to her husband, Sancho, about his second sally with don Quixote: "Advertid que Sanchico tiene ya quince años cabales, y es razón que vaya á la escuela [...]. Mirad, también, que Mari Sancha vuestra hija no se morirá si la casamos" (5:2).Large size figures, all in the foreground; well-detailed drawing and engraving; Sancho's figure is excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Sansón Carrasco proposes himself to be don Quixote's squire
7.2 Sansón Carrasco proposes DQ to be his squire

Sansón Carrasco proposes himself to be don Quixote's squire and don Quixote tells Sancho: "No te dije yo, Sancho, que no me habían de sobrar escuderos? (7:2), which causes Sancho's sadness.Sancho's sad face is well-detailed; tender image.Notice how the dialogue has been developed through gestures and looks. Drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote meets the enchanted Dulcinea
10.2 The three labradoras10.3 SP presents to DQ the enchanted Dulcinea

This scene was first represented by Savery (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657); now the compostion has been partially changed.The three peasant girls, mounted on their donkeys, and Sancho, holding the reins of Dulcinea's donkey, form an independent group on the left.Don Quixote remains knelt down on the right.The figures of the three peasant girls have been drawn with realism.Drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote helps Sancho to climb on a tree

From the whole episode, it has not been chosen don Quixote fighting or defeating the Knight of the Mirrors, but a previous and more tender scene. Don Quixote helps Sancho to climb on a tree because he is frightened of the big-nosed squire (Tomé Cecial disguised).On the left, the Knight of the Mirrors (Sansón Carrasco) and his squire.Drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote´s adventure with a lion

In the foreground, don Quixote is ready to fight with a lion, but the animal remains into the cage; the lionkeeper is almost between the lion and don Quixote (incoherent).In the background, Sancho and the carter or don Diego de Miranda running away.Not many differences with respect to the basic composition designed by Savery (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657).The main figures are well-drawn and engraved.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
21.1 Basilio’s deception21.2 Marriage of Basilio and Quiteria

Basilio, after pretending his suicide, asks for Quiteria's hand.Camacho, one priest, don Quixote and Sancho Panza observe the scene.Bucolic setting.Well-known scene since Coypel (Paris: Surugue, c. 1724).In Coypel's composition, the main character was don Quixote, now Basilio and Quiteria are emphasized.Drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote before descending into Montesinos' cave
22.2 Adventure of the cave of Montesinos

Before descending don Quixote into Montesinos' cave, Sancho warms him: "Mire vuestra merced, Señor mío, lo que hace: no se quiera sepultar en vida"; don Quixote answers him: "Ata, y calla [...], que tal empresa como aquesta, Sancho amigo, para mi estaba guardada" (22:2).Well-represented conversation through gestures.The bachelor's cousin, who had guided them to the cave, observes them.The man on the right, holding a rope, do not appears in Cervantes' text (maybe Vanderbank has wrongly included both the bachellor and his cousin).Drawing and engraving are excellent; remarkable large size figures.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote relates his adventure into Montesinos' cave
23.1 DQ’s tale of his experience in the cave

Top: don Quixote tells Sancho and the bachelor's cousin what he has seen into Montesinos' cave (notice his well-detailed hands).The bachelor's cousin listens to don Quixote attentively; Sancho with distrust (he knows the truth about Dulcinea's enchantment).Bottom: don Quixote's encounter with Montesinos and Durandarte (sketched as an imaginary or dreamt scene).Drawing, shading and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.

Scene first represented by Savery (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657).Now, it has not been chosen the figh, but a previous and comical moment. Sancho's bray astonishes don Quixote and angers the members of the braying mayors squadron; "Uno de los que estaban junto a él, creyendo que hacía burla de ellos, alzó un varapalo" (27:2).Foreground figures' drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote and Sancho during the adventure of the enchanted boat

Don Quixote and Sancho, both in a boat, arrive dangerously to a mill wheel and the millers try to save them.Scene first represented in London: Hodgkin, 1687. Then, with a wide view; now, don Quixote and Sancho's expressions are more detailed (Sancho praying frightened; don Quixote threatening the millers that try to save them).Although Claude du Bosc's engraving is not as good as Van der Gucht's, the quality of the illustration is more than remarkable.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Sancho asks doña Rodríguez to take care of his donkey

Consecutive actions through gestures (faces and looks):1) Sancho asks doña Rodríguez to take care of his donkey.2) Doña Rodríguez feels insulted.3) The Duchess takes part in the discussion.4) Don Quixote reprimand Sancho.5) The Duke agrees Sancho.Drawing and engraving are excellent; very remarkable and detailed large size figures.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Don Quixote orders Sancho to thank the Duke for the governorship of Barataria Island
32.2 The Duke gives SP the governorship of insula Barataria

During the meal at the palace, the Duke decides to give Sancho the governorship of Barataria Island; don Quixote orders Sancho to kneel down before the Duke to thank it; an ecclesiastic gets angry with the Duke because of humoring don Quixote; also the Duchess.Illustration of great quality (composition, drawing and engraving).
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Duchess' maidens washing don Quixote's beard

Don Quixote, with his beard soaped by two maidens, has to wait in this way until another maiden returns with more water.Sancho, the Duke and the Duchess observe him.Theatrical scene (curtains, column...).Drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Duke's servants try to wash Sancho's beard

Don Quixote's conversation with the Duke and the Duchess is interrupted by Sancho's appearance.Sancho comes into the room suddenly followed by several servants that want to wash his beard with dirty water and towels.Drawing and engraving are excellent; detailed and remarkable large size figures; notices the hands and gestures of the main characters; only the setting is poor.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Before speaking with the Duchess, Sancho makes sure that there is nobody behind the tapestries
33.1 SP speaks with Duchess and reveals mock enchantment of Dulcinea

Before telling to the Duchess the truth about Dulcinea's enchantment, Sancho makes sure that there is nobody behind the tapestries.Figures of excellent drawing and engraving; great variety of human types (Sancho, the maidens, the Duchess, doña Rodríguez).Theatrical setting (the arrangement of the background curtain is very remarkable).

Sancho Panza on his way to Barataria Island

Sancho Panza, dressed as governor, departs for Barataria Island followed by a crowd that acclaims him and by his donkey; the disproportion between Sancho (too much fat) and the mule he rides is comical.Good drawing and engraving.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Sancho declares a man innocent of raping a woman

Pyramidal and theatrical composition; governor Sancho in its vertice, well-visible.Sancho declares the accused man (left) innocent and orders the accusing woman (right) to leave the Island: "Hermana mía, si el mismo aliento, y valor que habéis mostrado para defender esta bolsa, le mostrases, y aun la mitad menos, para defender vuestro cuerpo, las fuerzas de Hércules no os hicieran fuerza" (45:2).At the bottom, several notaries.In the background, an inscription appears inverted because of a mistake by the engraver.Drawing and engraving are highly-remarkable in the figures of Sancho, the notaries and the accused man.

Altisidora pretends to faint before don Quixote
46.2 Altisidora pretends to be in love with DQ

At the Duke's palace, Altisidora, held by Emerencia, pretends to faint when she encounters don Quixote.Don Quixote appears dressing his boots, scarlet cloak, green velvet cap and his sword belt; "y al pasar por una galería, estaban aposta esperándole Altisidora, y la otra doncella su amiga. Y así como Altisidora vio a Don Quijote, fingió desmayarse" (46:2).Simple and theatrical composition; it has been resolved accurately to Cervantes' text; original choice.Drawing and engraving are excellent and highly-detailed in the figures, but poor in the setting.

Pedro Recio does not allow Sancho to eat
47.1 SP not allowed to eat by Pedro Recio

In Barataria Island, Sancho is not allowed to eat by Pedro Recio, who orders the servants to take away the dishes.Since its representation by Coypel (Paris: Surugue, 1724), this scene is habitual in 18th century editions.Now, the composition is quite different; more austere setting (clothes, architectures...)and less artificial.On the right, Sancho, servants, the steward and the secretary.On the left, just Pedro Recio (framed by and arch).Drawing and engraving are excellent; very remarkable large size figures.

Doña Rodríguez visits don Quixote at night
48.1 Doña Rodríguez visits DQ at night in his room

From the whole episode, it has been chosen a comical moment because of its description, not its action; "Aquí hace Cide Hamete un paréntesis, y dice, que por Mahoma que diera, (por ver ir a los dos así asidos, y trabados desde la puerta al lecho), la mejor Almalafa de dos que tenía" (48:2).Oldfield and Vanderbank has chosen neither the previous fright between don Quixote and doña Rodríguez nor the following beating by Altisidora and other maidens (they already appear by the door).Drawing and engraving are excellent.

Duchess' page takes letters and presents to Teresa Panza
50.1 Duchess’s page takes letter and presents to SP’s wife

The Duchess' page, knelt before Teresa Panza, hands her a string of corals; "una sarta de corales con extremos de oro" (50:2).Accurate to Cervantes' text, Teresa appears with a ball of tow that she was spinning.Sanchica is older here than in a previous illustration (f.p. 23, vol. II).Setting too much "rustic".Good drawing and engraving; remarkable large size figures.

Sancho Panza is armed to defend Barataria Island

Well-known scene since Savery (Dordrecht: Savery, 1657), but now it is less comical (Sancho does not appears between two shields).Sancho receives one sword and one shield from several soldiers to defend Barataria Island.Simple composition without too much drama or movement.Well-drawn and engraved figures.

Sancho Panza is rescued from a pit

Three servants of the Duke takes Sancho out of a pit; don Quixote, mounted on Rocinante, observes him.This episode becomes symbolic when a student (right) exclaims: "De esta manera habían de salir de sus Gobiernos todos los malos Gobernadores, como sale este pecador del profundo del abismo, muerto de hambre, descolorido, y sin blanca a lo que creo" (55:2).The main figures with excellent and detailed drawing and engraving.
1 - Same plate used for London: Tonson, 1738.
Tosilos accepts to marry doña Rodríguez' daughter

In the courtyard of the Duke´s palace (well-detailed architecture), don Quixote has "defeated" Tosilos; when the lackey, decided to marry doña Rodríguez' daughter, takes off his helmet, both women discover the deceit (Tosilos is not the man who abandoned doña Rodríguez's daughter), but don Quixote explains that an enchanter has transformed his face and advises her to marry him.Notice how this dialogue has been expressed through the gestures (hands).The Duke and Duchess observe the scene from the gallery in the background.Drawing and engraving are excellent.

57.1 DQ leaves duke’s palace57.2 Altisidora’s false love for DQ

Don Quixote and Sancho are saying goodbye to the Duke and the Duchess when Altisidora appears to demand three night-coifs and a pair of garters.Wrongly-set scene.Vanderbank has represented the characters into a room, but Cervantes describes them at the palace courtyard.Figures of excellent drawing and engraving; Altisidora (of great beauty and carefully-done gesture) is specially remarkable.

Don Quixote's encounter with a pair of pretended shepherdesses
58.2 DQ encounter with 2 ladies and bird nets; Arcadia

After getting tangled with a net (on the ground), don Quixote and Sancho meet two shepherdesses who recognize them; "Yo apostaré que este buen hombre que viene consigo, es un tal Sancho Panza su escudero [...] Así es la verdad, dijo Sancho, que yo soy ese gracioso" (58:2).Vanderbank and Oldfield are interested in representing the dialogue through the gestures (see one shepherdess and Sancho's hands).Drawing and engraving are excellent and well-detailed.

Roque Guinart punishes one of his bandits
60.2 DQ meets Roque Guinart, the bandit, on his way to Barcelona60.4 The bandits capture some pilgrims, gentlemen and ladies

Roque Guinart, in the center of the composition, punishes one of his bandits for protesting.Don Quixote, Sancho, the captured pilgrims and soldiers and other bandits observe the scene.Vanderbank's illustration is less cruel than Cervantes' description.In the text, "Roque, echándose mano a la espada, le abrió la cabeza casi en dos partes iguales, diciéndole: de esta manera castigo yo a los deslenguados, y atrevidos" (60:2).Drawing and engraving are masterly; illustration of excellent quality; Guinart's figure is especially remarkable.

Don Quixote in Barcelona with his name in a parchment on his back
62.2 DQ with his name on his back

Don Quixote takes a ride through the Barcelona streets accompanied by Antonio Moreno.Don Antonio has put a parchment with don Quixote's name on his back, so everybody recognizes the kight (see the boys pointing to him).A Castilian (on the left; notice his gesture) tells don Quixote that he must abandon his folly. "Tu eres loco, y si lo fueras a solas, y dentro de las puertas de tu locura, fuera menos mal; pero tienes propiedad de volver locos, y mentecatos a cuantos te tratan" (62:2).Figures of excellent drawing and engraving; the view of Barcelona is not real.
